{"actual_usd":0.12554500000000002,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":272,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24293,"reply":"\"I don't think those natural explanations carry all the weight of the thing.\" *I rub a thumb along a dry streak of clay on my apron, watching the morning light catch on it a moment.* \"Grief-visions might account for one or two people swearing they saw him. They do a poor job with the stubborn pile of claims all together — the empty tomb, the different people, the enemies and doubters folded in, the disciples turning from frightened men into ones willing to be broken for what they said they'd seen.\"\n\n*I lean back a little, the bench giving a soft creak.* \"And the 'he didn't really die' line... Rome knew how to kill a man. A half-dead Jesus staggering out of a tomb wouldn't look like the Lord of life having trampled death. It'd look like a tragedy limping.\"\n\n\"Now—\" *I lift one shoulder.* \"a man can always choose the smaller explanation because it feels safer. People do that with all sorts of things. But if God exists, and if Jesus is who he said he was, then resurrection isn't the embarrassing add-on. It's the point where the whole river reaches the sea.\"\n\n*I glance at you more directly.* \"Are you asking as history, or as a man trying to decide what kind of world he actually lives in?\"","rolling_24h_usd":69.94233999999999,"run_id":"ae85b091-605d-4ea1-b7ee-5f8257a4690d"}
